Exploring Red Wine

by Anthony “Ant” Cassetta

Introduction

Data Set: Red Wine Quality

Prompt question: Which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines?

This tidy dataset contains 1,599 entries of red wines with 11 features on the chemical properties of the wine. 1 feature acting as a line ID, which will be ignored, and one label holding the rated quality.

At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (terrible) and 10 (excellent).

## [1] 1599   13

The output above confirms the provided counts on the data-set. We have approximately 1600 rows each containing 13 variables total, 11 related to chemical properties, 1 acting as an id number of the row, and 1 holing the quality rating.

Another notable characteristic, there are no wines scored below a 3, and none scored above an 8. This makes sense for 2 reasons. firstly, the scores are likely a rounded average computed from the three wine reviewers individual scores. Logically its unlikely all three reviews would grant a perfect 0 or a perfect 10. Additionally, know the data is tidy. It’s likely if there where a few extreme cases these were simply omitted.

Univariate Analysis

Overview of Dataset:

1599 rows, 13 columns Every column contains a numeric value, either and integer or general numeric. 11 chemical variables, 1 index number and 1 quality rating.

Features of Interest:

The main feature of interest is the quality rating. This analysis will explore what variable correlations exist and possible causation of a higher quality rating.

Possible Supporting Features in the Dataset:

Initial supporting variables include Alcohol percentage, Total Sulfur Dioxide content, Volatile acidity, and residual Sugar. I’d also like to explore PH level and acidity.

Augmented Features:

Several of the variables posses a long-tailed or skewed distribution. In order to visualize a more normalized distribution log 10 has been applied to the following variables; Sulfates, Residual Sugar, Chlorides and Sulfur Dioxide.

In the above plot, we can see the distribution of alcohol percentage across quality rating and with the mean percentages overlay (the blue line).

With this visualization we can see an upward trend of the mean. This trend makes sense when we recall the same trend was reported in our summary of alcohol data above. The visualization adds some much need perspective. For example, we can see that density of the points across qualities is quite variable.

For instance, quality 5, 6, 7 are all rather densely packed around the mean in contrast 3, 4, 8 are rather spread out. Also, notice that peak at quality 4, if you look closely at quality of 4 you’ll notice an outlier. This outlier explains the deviation from the trend.

Visually we can speculate a weak positive correlation between alcohol and quality rating but its difficult to tell how strong that correlation is. Lets mathematically check our conclusion with Pearson’s Correlation.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  quality and alcohol
## t = 21.639, df = 1597, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4373540 0.5132081
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4761663

The result of calculating Pearson’s product-moment correlation between quality rating and alcohol percentage is the (rounded) coefficient = 0.5 according to the scale of coefficients this is scored as a moderate correlation.

So although we cannot infer causation, we can say that there is an observable relation between higher quality wines and higher alcohol percentage.

Bivariate Analysis

Relationship observations:

Investigating quality against alcohol percentage showed a medium correlation. indicating that a higher alcohol content tended to have a higher rating in some cases.

Quality against total SO2 indicated a weak negative correlation. Indicating that sometimes a higher rating had less total SO2, but frequently not. The same can be said when comparing total SO2 per alcohol percentage.

In other words neither Alcohol percentage nor SO2 can be exclusively credited with causing a quality to be higher or lower. These weak and medium correlations do imply that they have an influence, especially in the case of alcohol content.

I, not knowing much about wine, expected the total SO2 level to be more correlated to the alcohol percentage than it turned out to be.

My reasoning being SO2 is used as a preservative to prevent the wine from spoiling so logically I figured higher alcohol concentration would negate the need for preservatives. Recall from the the plot, the trend line does slope downward as percentage rises, but this slope is gradual. Visually displaying that there is a weak correlation, but alcohol percentage clearly does not significantly influence higher or lower total SO2.

These discoveries lead me to believe that no two variable alone can influence the quality rating significantly.

The strongest relationship:

The strongest relationship I found was only a moderate level of correlation between Alcohol percentage and quality. Not enough to hypothesize alcohol content -> quality causation but, enough to explore multivariate plots focusing on quality and alcohol percentage.

Multivariate Plots Section

There doesn’t seem to be any ground breaking information in this plot, we do know that there is an amount of residual sugar, that amount is most often between 2 and 4 and that the amount left over is not noticeably effected by alcohol percentage or fixed acidity.

First thing we notice is the way the quality ratings are broken up horizontally. For example we can quickly see that wines rated with a quality of 5 tend to be between 9% and 10% alcohol. The range of volatile acidity tends to be larger, but there are distinct clusters. for example 0.7 - 0.74.

The above plot shows the fixed acidity level by density of each wine. The color represents that particular wines pH level.

We already know from the bivariant exploration that density and fixed acidity have a positive correlation. With pH added we’re seeing the most common pH level is by far between 3 - 3.5. We can also see a dense cluster of that particular pH level between 4 and 8 fixed acidity by 0.995 and ~0.997 density

This tells us that within those ranges of density and fixed acidity pH level tends to be between 3 and 3.5.

An interesting thing in this plot is the outliers, look at the top right. Something funny is happening with those wines. they’re well beyond the 3rd quartile of both density and fixed acidity as well as being one of the less common pH levels. It would be interesting to dive in and find out why.

Multivariate Analysis

Through the analysis I’ve found a handful of weak to moderate correlations. These are interesting findings that indicate no two features seem to have a substantial impact on quality rating but instead a set of 3 or more features must be at play.

I found it interesting that residual sugar was unaffected by alcohol percentage, or the wines fixed acidity level. I had expected higher alcohol percentage, meaning more sugars converted to alcohol, would lead to less leftover sugar. The most common amount of residual sugar was between 2-4 units and it was pretty evenly spread across the plot

Final Takeaway Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The first plot we visualized displays the counts of wine per Quality rating. This plot is important because I’m able to clearly see the distributions. Right away I know that if I perform more analysis using quality as a variable I am likely to see large clusters of data at qualities of 5 and 6. It also lets me know that if I do not see such a pattern there is something interesting worth looking into.

This information also provides perspective of how I might subset the data for comparison. Say I examined only entries of rating 5 and 6 I can identify correlations and trends. Then examine a smaller sample, like the wines rated higher than 6 to attempt to identify significant differences that might indicate a correlation with a higher rating.

Plot Two

Description Two

We can see the distribution of alcohol percentage across quality with a line representing mean percentages overlayed.

This plot is important because it’s indicating both a trend and a lack of causation. First take notice of the density around quality 5 and 6. We already know that makes sense because 5 and 6 have a much larger count of wines than any other rating.

If we look at the mean line we notice an upward trend. With the exception of quality level 4, which in this plot is being effected by an outlier.

Now this trend does imply a positive correlation between alcohol percentage and quality rating. It does not imply causation, if you look at the data of quality 8 you’ll notice its sparse and quite spread out. In this case the mean is informative but not the most reliable measurement.

We can reinforce our conclusion with Pearson’s Correlation. The correlation coefficient for quality and alcohol is (rounded) 0.5 indicating there is indeed a moderate coloration.

Reflection

I began by looking at each variable to get a feel for the data. 1599 rows of data comprised of 11 variables and the quality rating. After exploring individual variables and taking note of interesting or anomalous events. This initial look provided some conclusions. The mode Quality rating is 5, the mean Quality rating is ~6. The largest counts of wines fell in quality rating 5 and 6. Both quality 5 and 6 have counts over 600, where as the counts for 3, 4, 7 and 8 are all below 200 and 0, 2, 9 and 10 have none at all. These findings were useful when I later began to compare two and more variables, I wasn’t surprised when I found items clustering around quality’s of 5 and 6, but no items present below 3 or above 8.

When I began trying to find correlations between The quality rating and variable factors such as alcohol percentage, total amount of Sulfur Dioxide, fixed acidity level…etc. My exploration lead me to the conclusion that none of these features individually have significant sway over the quality rating of the wines. I was able to determine that Quality has a negative correlation with Volatile Acidity (r = -0.4) and a positive coloration with alcohol percentage (r = 0.5). These correlations do not prove any kind of causation but they might prove to be key features in a larger combination.

Limitations to this project are firstly, unclear units of measure. I found this data I can make guesses about standard units of measure for wine but at the end of the day I can’t be sure these measurements are accurate. The rating system of the wines is also rather a mystery. The introduction to the data states each wine was rated by at least three reviewers but it is not clarified how these ratings are applied. There are no unique identifiers about the wine it self in the data. So, I do not know if the total reviews are averaged per-wine and placed in the data set or if each wine exists multiple times throughout the data set.

If a client is looking to improve their wines rating, I would suggest clarifying the above points. For example if each wine is listed multiple times per review it would be possible to understand which reviewer biases are being included. Say, one reviewer often highly rates wines with a higher alcohol content. A downside of this approach could lead the client to only allow their wine to be reviewed by reviewers who favor their type of wine but that’s a risk regardless of the data.
